<rss version="2.0" xmlns:atom="http://www.w3.org/2005/Atom"><channel><title><![CDATA[The Atlantic - MOST-POPULAR]]></title><link/> https://www.theatlantic.com/most-popular/<atom:link href="https://rsshub.app/theatlantic/most-popular" rel="self" type="application/rss+xml"></atom:link><description><![CDATA[The Atlantic - MOST-POPULAR - Made with love by RSSHub(https://github.com/DIYgod/RSSHub)]]></description><generator> RS集线器</generator><webmaster>i@diygod.me (DIYgod)</webmaster><language> zh-cn</language><lastbuilddate> 2023 年 8 月 1 日，星期二 12:11:52 GMT</lastbuilddate><ttl> 120 </ttl><item><title><![CDATA[The Actor Who Documented His Grief—And Shared It With the World]]></title><description><![CDATA[<div>两年前妻子去世后，理查德·E·格兰特开始拍摄自己谈论丧亲之痛的视频，创造了失去亲人后的非凡生活记录。 <br><figure><img src="https://cdn.theatlantic.com/thumbor/8ny6MtCE5Eq8BE0Kxg8D-bkQGhM=/0x0:3307x4134/648x810/media/img/2023/07/31/eyevine03346058/original.jpg" alt="演员理查德·E·格兰特闭着眼睛的肖像" referrerpolicy="no-referrer"><figcaption>索菲亚·斯普林 / Guardian / eyevine/ Redux</figcaption></figure>在镜头前，演员理查德·E·格兰特倾向于散发出一种不为人知的、阴暗的气质：无论他的角色表达了多少，你总是能感觉到字里行间有一些无法完全校准的东西。在他的新回忆录<a data-event-element="inline link" href="https://tertulia.com/book/a-pocketful-of-happiness-a-memoir-richard-e-grant/9781668030691?affiliate_id=atl-347"><em>《一袋幸福》</em></a>中，格兰特优雅地将自己的职业生涯概括为数十年的“极简主义恶行”。他的角色包罗万象，从享乐主义的浪荡演员（《 <em>Withnail and I</em> 》）到专制的女子乐队经理（ <em>《Spice World》</em> ），再到迷人的犯罪同伙（他在<em>《你能原谅我吗？</em> 》中获得奥斯卡提名的角色），但如果他们有共同的共同点属性，那就是如果他们偷了你的钱包，你甚至不会感到惊讶。<br><br>然而在生活中，格兰特将诚实变成了一种富有创造力、极其精致的艺术形式。大约两年前，与他结婚 35 年的妻子、方言教练琼·华盛顿 (Joan Washington) 因肺癌去世，在失去她的几个月后，他在 Instagram 上记录了丧亲之痛的片段。在典型的视频中，他的脸稍微偏离中心，视线远离镜头。他看上去衣衫不整。他看起来很闹鬼。 “令人难以理解的是，我们再也不能互相接触或交谈了，”他在一卷中说道。在另一张照片中，他拍摄了自己穿过树林的情景，简单地说：“一次一步。”<br><br>在悲痛之中——这是最孤立的状态——格兰特迅速建立了社区。 “在您与我们分享的这些深思熟虑的视频中，我找到了令人难以置信的安慰；他们美丽的诚实，他们的痛苦，但总是在美好生活的更大马赛克中仔细地重新构建每一件作品，”最近当格兰特分享他母亲去世的消息时，一位女士评论道。总的来说，这些上传的内容可能会让人迷失方向，这也是它们作为失去亲人后的生活记录如此具有启发性的原因。格兰特发布了来自朋友家的视频；他推广自己的项目；他重新创作了<em>《Withnail》</em>中的场景来打发隔离期间的 10 天时间。但一切的根本原因是琼的缺席——正如他在澳大利亚海滩上散步时在一篇帖子中所说的那样，这种感觉“就像一只没有壳的老乌龟”。<br><br>今年春天早些时候，当我在格兰特位于伦敦西南部的家中会见他时，他似乎仍然对过去几年的悲伤、生产力和公众反应的融合感到茫然。在他的文学经纪人和女儿的敦促下，他写了一本关于琼生命最后几个月的回忆录，其中穿插了他职业生涯过去几年的故事。由此产生的书《一袋幸福》（ <em>A Pocketful of Happiness）</em> ——本月在美国出版——以琼在去世前给他的遗嘱命名，保证如果他能试着找到一点点来感激每一个人，他就会没事。单日。 “在我们的婚姻中，她以前从来没有想到过这句话，”66 岁的格兰特说道，他身材修长，穿着黑色灯芯绒裤子和黑色衬衫，腿上抱着女儿的猫。 “我想，如果我们中有人说过这句话，我们就会得出结论，这听起来像是霍尔马克卡片上的内容。但事实证明，这是一个非常深刻的生活准则。”<br><br>他决定将最迷人的高潮（奥斯卡奖、与奥利维亚·科尔曼在贝蒂·戴维斯以前拥有的房子里唱卡拉 OK）和最惨淡的低谷（琼的诊断、有一天格兰特无意中使用<em>“终端”</em>一词时她的愤怒）共同构成这本书的叙述他说，这是出于他想要准确捕捉大多数人的生活的愿望。 1986 年，也就是格兰特与琼结婚的那一年，格兰特充其量只是一名打工演员，负责拼凑地区戏剧片尾字幕和电视电影。在经历了九个月的痛苦失业之后，丹尼尔·戴·刘易斯拒绝了他的一个角色：布鲁斯·罗宾逊的半自传故事片中华丽、浑身湿透的威斯奈尔。这份工作是一个巨大的突破。第一周排练结束时，怀孕27周的琼就早产了。他们的第一个孩子蒂芙尼只活了半个小时，她的肺部尚未发育成熟，无法自行呼吸。 “我不认为你能克服它，”格兰特说。 “你可以绕过它。”<br><br> <em>《一袋幸福》</em>捕捉到了如何在灾难性消息发生时完全摆脱困境，即使是在持续的承诺和繁杂的日常任务中。格兰特写道，在等待琼的放射治疗开始时整理花园，收拾起琼的衣服盒子以腾出空间，并为她可能再也不会穿它们而感到震惊。他们的关系是这本书引人入胜的中心支柱——一位极其注重隐私的苏格兰方言教练和一位来自南部非洲斯威士兰、比她小十岁、长期过度兴奋、心直口快的演员之间一段不可预测的持久爱情。在他们关系之初，琼的职业生涯已经很稳固，而格兰特则担任服务员。在他们的婚姻过程中，地位的平衡发生了变化，但他对我说，他们从未失去联系：“一段从 1983 年 1 月在床上谈话开始的关系，以床上握着彼此的手而结束。” 38 年后与她交谈。”<br><br> <a href="https://www.theatlantic.com/books/archive/2023/05/emma-straub-interview-this-time-tomorrow-grief/674035/">阅读：现代生活的决定性情感</a><br><br>在这本书去年首次出版的欧洲和澳大利亚，格兰特带着这本书进行了巡回演出，举办了一场戏剧表演，其中融入了琼的视频和照片；在第二幕中，观众有机会分享自己的悲伤。他愿意表现出一种通常被认为是私人的经历——如此积极地颠覆我们的感觉，即“正确”的方式来度过它是坚忍的、孤独的——是惊人的。他对在丧亲之痛后立即给予人们空间的不言而喻的传统不屑一顾，而这正是“你需要人们倾诉的时刻”。对于那些根本不承认琼死讯的人，他的态度明显很凶猛。今年早些时候，他发布了一段视频，内容是在法国偶遇一对夫妇，他们是他认识 25 年的朋友，但他们在街上明显避开了他，而不是对没有联系表示遗憾。 “我感觉自己好像被打了一巴掌，”他告诉我，气得浑身发抖。<br><br>在 Instagram 上，正如他的许多评论者所明确指出的那样，他的言论产生了强烈的认可感。他愿意公开哀悼，这引发了一些问题：如果分享悲伤可以让人感觉宣泄，为什么要隐藏悲伤呢？为什么悲伤的配偶、父母、孩子应该安静地表达呢？为什么我们对那些正在经历巨大损失的人的本能反应是躲起来并躲起来？ “我认为（人们）担心他们要么会入侵，要么你会像人行道上的果冻一样崩溃，”格兰特说。他承认，他仍然有被悲伤“折磨”的日子，唯一能做的就是屈服并等待它过去，但他也有美好的日子，灿烂的日子，充满幸福的日子。 。他在导演埃默拉尔德·芬内尔（《 <a data-event-element="inline link" href="https://www.theatlantic.com/culture/archive/2020/12/emerald-fennell-promising-young-woman-subverting-femininity/617467/"><em>前途无量的年轻女子</em></a>》）备受期待的第二部长片<em>《索尔特伯恩》</em>中扮演角色。他还计划出演萨姆·门德斯和阿曼多·伊安努奇关于超级英雄系列的新 HBO 讽刺剧，以及与保罗·路德和珍娜·奥尔特加合作的 A24 的<em>《独角兽之死》</em> 。 （后者是今年夏天在演员罢工期间获准拍摄的少数独立项目之一。）<br><br>他认为，他现在所做的很多事情——巡回售书、现场活动——放在过去都太令人生畏了。 “琼之死的重新调整让我意识到，你所担心的所有这些事情都与自我有关，”他说。 “处理死亡是如此灾难性的，以至于它简化了其他一切。”<br><br></div> ]]>;</description><pubDate> Tue, 01 Aug 2023 11:30:00 GMT</pubDate><guid ispermalink="false"> https://www.theatlantic.com/culture/archive/2023/08/richard-e-grant-a-pocketful-of-happiness-interview/674876/</guid><link/> https://www.theatlantic.com/culture/archive/2023/08/richard-e-grant-a-pocketful-of-happiness-interview/674876/</item><item><title><![CDATA[The First Great Crisis of a Second Trump Term]]></title><description><![CDATA[<div>如果再次当选，这位前总统将采取行动消除他的法律麻烦。宪政混乱和政治混乱将会随之而来。 <br><figure><img src="https://cdn.theatlantic.com/thumbor/hoCwMd080m-RR1ppr-lByIQOMYw=/0x0:4800x2700/960x540/media/img/mt/2023/07/trump_/original.jpg" alt="特朗普站在讲台上的一张竞选海报前并举起另一张竞选海报的照片" referrerpolicy="no-referrer"><figcaption>布莱恩·斯奈德/路透社</figcaption></figure>他的支持者和反对者都认为，如果前总统唐纳德·特朗普能够赢得 2024 年总统选举，他的法律危险就会消失。这是一个很大的错误。 2024 年特朗普当选不会解决任何问题。这将引发一场震动全国的总统合法性危机。 2024 年的特朗普意味着混乱——几乎肯定还会有另一次弹劾。<br><br>特朗普<a data-event-element="inline link" href="https://www.politico.com/interactives/2023/trump-criminal-investigations-cases-tracker-list/#jan-six">不断增加的犯罪曝光</a>发生在两个不同的联邦司法管辖区——佛罗里达州和哥伦比亚特区——以及两个不同的州司法管辖区——纽约和佐治亚州。可能还会有更多。<br><br>作为总统，特朗普本身没有权力直接撤销任何这些诉讼程序。他必须通过其他人来行动。例如，特朗普可以尝试的最接近单方面的事情就是总统自我赦免。那合法吗？特朗普<a data-event-element="inline link" href="https://www.nytimes.com/2018/06/04/us/politics/trump-pardon-power-constitution.html">断言</a>确实如此。只有最高法院才能做出最终裁决，这给特朗普带来了巨大的风险，因为法院可能会拒绝。自我赦免<a data-event-element="inline link" href="https://papers.ssrn.com/sol3/papers.cfm?abstract_id=3728908">违背了总统赦免权的历史和逻辑</a>。一个<a data-event-element="inline link" href="https://poll.qu.edu/poll-release?releaseid=3874">正在与自己的合法性问题作斗争的</a>最高法院会冒如此严重的风险，以自己的声誉来保护特朗普免受正义的审判吗？<br><br> <a href="https://www.theatlantic.com/ideas/archive/2023/06/donald-trump-fox-bret-baier-interview-fear/674467/">汤姆·尼科尔斯：特朗普似乎很害怕，非常害怕</a><br><br>特朗普有一种方法可以避免最高法院对他做出不利裁决的风险。他可以命令他的司法部长命令特别检察官不要对他的自我赦免提起诉讼，然后命令司法部在法庭上辩称，除了特别检察官之外，没有人有权提起诉讼。<br><br>然后事情就变得复杂了。总检察长会这样做吗？特别检察官会提交吗？律政司的专业人士会<a data-event-element="inline link" href="https://www.axios.com/2022/06/23/jeffrey-clark-jan6-hearing-trump">继续留任</a>吗？国会和国内会发生什么？<br><br>如果你假设特朗普无法赢得多数普选（鉴于他两次未能赢得普选），情况就会变得更加复杂。如果他重返办公室，他很可能会因为选举团的侥幸而这样做。<br><br>因此，被刑事起诉的总统必须辩称，他有权自我赦免，并且他有权禁止检察官在法庭上对此提出质疑，<i>而且</i>他还可以命令司法部在法庭上与任何其他人进行对抗。寻求代表检察官提起诉讼。他必须基于自己代表人民意志的主张来完成所有这一切，尽管他可能没有赢得多数民众选票。<br><br><a href="https://www.theatlantic.com/ideas/archive/2023/06/trump-indictment/674345/">大卫·A·格雷厄姆：这份起诉书是不同的</a><br><br>毕竟，他<a data-event-element="inline link" href="https://www.nytimes.com/article/trump-investigations-civil-criminal.html">仍然会在州法院面临起诉</a>，而他在州法院没有赦免权。因此，对于他的下一步行动，他必须命令司法部辩称州法院对现任总统没有刑事管辖权。他<a data-event-element="inline link" href="https://www.nbcnews.com/politics/2016-election/trump-says-he-could-shoot-somebody-still-maintain-support-n502911">可以在纽约市第五大道或任何州的街道上开枪射杀某人</a>，而在他的任期结束之前， <a data-event-element="inline link" href="https://www.politico.com/news/2019/10/23/trump-lawyer-prosecuted-shooting-someone-055648">没有人能对此采取任何行动</a>。<br><br>随着这种荒谬的情况逐渐显现，特朗普在尝试自我赦免后的几天内很可能不会<i>设立</i>司法部。将会出现大规模辞职，而且可能无法确认美国参议院高级官员的继任者。 （特朗普第一届政府<a data-event-element="inline link" href="https://www.justsecurity.org/72456/at-least-15-trump-officials-do-not-hold-their-positions-lawfully/">一再依赖</a>代理任命者，而不是参议院确认的官员，但第二届政府故意绕过参议院以关闭法院，这本身就会引发宪法危机。）<br><br>特朗普前往同一目的地的其他路线也遇到了同样的问题。特朗普可以尝试采取更间接的策略来终止联邦起诉：命令特别检察官杰克·史密斯下台，如果他拒绝，就解雇他。这种方法绕过了法院，但它在很大程度上取决于找到一位顺从的总检察长来取消起诉书，以及国会对看似彻底废除联邦执法的默许。联邦司法部将解散。不管怎样，州案件将继续进行。特朗普丑闻将是国会唯一的事务。<br><br>特朗普本人可能并不关心：即使是弹劾，他也没有受到惩罚，也没有被吓倒。但特朗普在该国领导着少数派，而第二个总统任期将产生的永久性危机将导致 2026 年民主党在国会取得压倒性胜利，甚至足以撼动特朗普领导的共和党。<br><br>特朗普可能会想象他手头上有一场一劳永逸的战斗：猛烈打击，快速打击，然后安安静静地享受不法权力的腐败特权。如果是这样，他和他的追随者就是在自欺欺人。整个任期都被围绕特朗普利用总统权力保护自己免受涉嫌犯罪后果的斗争所消耗。<br><br> <a href="https://www.theatlantic.com/ideas/archive/2021/01/a-self-pardon-wont-save-trump/617592/">本杰明·威茨：特朗普的自我赦免幻想将遭遇残酷的现实</a><br><br>特朗普过去在遇到麻烦时的做法是通过陷入另一桩丑闻来转移人们对另一桩丑闻的注意力。也许这一次他会试图切断对乌克兰的援助，或者炸毁北约，或者对变装皇后发起一场文化战争。但这些噱头都不会分散美国人的注意力。他们只会让他们更加痛苦。<br><br>特朗普寻求自我赦免并不等同于<a data-event-element="inline link" href="https://constitutioncenter.org/blog/the-nixon-pardon-in-retrospect">杰拉尔德·福特总统赦免前总统理查德·尼克松</a>，这一决定当时不受欢迎，但最终被许多最激烈的批评者和大多数公众接受。自我赦免的尝试将会震动整个国家。它永远不会被认为是出于公益、两党共同目的而采取的合法行为。愤怒并未平息。体质上的伤害无法痊愈。<br><br>特朗普连任总统只会带来永远不会平息的分裂、混乱和瘫痪。它也不会停止——直到总统任期本身结束，甚至可能还没有结束。<br><br></div> ]]>;</description><pubDate> Tue, 01 Aug 2023 11:00:00 GMT</pubDate><guid ispermalink="false"> https://www.theatlantic.com/ideas/archive/2023/08/constitutional-crisis-second-trump-term/674872/</guid><link/> https://www.theatlantic.com/ideas/archive/2023/08/constitutional-crisis-second-trump-term/674872/ </item><item><title><![CDATA[A Defense of the Supreme Court]]></title><description><![CDATA[<div>它最近的任期是对该机构的赞扬，而不是批评者所说的令人憎恶。 <br><figure><img src="https://cdn.theatlantic.com/thumbor/u17KcQBD3hP_vZJfrurk9ojF5f0=/0x0:3300x1856/960x540/media/img/mt/2023/07/h_15745641/original.jpg" alt="最高法院" referrerpolicy="no-referrer"><figcaption>姜海云 / 纽约时报 / Redux</figcaption></figure>去年夏天对堕胎做出裁决后，最高法院不可避免地遭到攻击。<i>多布斯诉杰克逊妇女健康案</i>中的多数决定——宪法中没有堕胎权——打破了大多数公众支持的长期先例，同时剥夺了数以千万计的人珍视的权利，这些因素引发了法院几十年来从未见过如此严重的强烈反对。<br><br>令人震惊且难以理解的是，最高法院最近一届任期始于 2022 年 10 月，最终于今年夏天宣布了裁决，同样遭到强烈反对。该术语<a data-event-element="inline link" href="https://www.oyez.org/cases/2022">总共包含 60 个案例</a>。无党派国家宪法中心<a data-event-element="inline link" href="https://constitutioncenter.org/blog/significant-supreme-court-cases-in-the-2022-2023-term">将其中 13 起案件标记为重大案件</a>。总而言之，它们表明最高法院与公众舆论大体一致，其法官们形成了跨越意识形态界限的不断变化的联盟。<br><br>但中左翼批评家对这个术语提出了截然不同的解释。他们将中右翼的裁决视为对最高法院糟糕性的确认，即使不是其非法性。<br><br> “这不是一个正常的法院，”总统乔·拜登在最高法院裁定学院和大学不能在招生中实施基于种族歧视候选人的平权行动政策后<a data-event-element="inline link" href="https://www.msnbc.com/deadline-white-house/watch/biden-supreme-court-has-done-more-to-unravel-basic-rights-than-any-other-in-recent-history-it-s-not-normal-185930821610">表示</a>。 “它在阐明基本权利和基本判决方面所做的工作比近代历史上任何法院都多。”<br><br>众议院少数党领袖哈基姆·杰弗里斯<a data-event-element="inline link" href="https://www.axios.com/2023/06/29/congress-democrats-supreme-court-affirmative-action">宣称，</a> “最高法院的极端分子再次更有兴趣将他们的右翼意识形态强加给美国人民。”<br><br>进步民主党众议员罗·卡纳 (Ro Khanna) <a data-event-element="inline link" href="https://www.theguardian.com/us-news/2023/jul/01/ro-khanna-congressman-progressive-supreme-court-term-limits">告诉</a><i>《卫报》</i> ，“当你看到这个法院在妇女权利、种族平等、投票权、环境、年轻人面临的挑战、LGBTQ+ 方面是多么脱节。”权利，然后你就知道他们只是脱节了。其中许多人无法赢得捕狗者的选举。”<br><br> “最高法院失控了”， <i>《新共和</i>》的<i> </i>编辑迈克尔·托马斯基 (Michael Tomasky) 在为该杂志报道法院的筹款活动中<a data-event-element="inline link" href="https://newrepublic.com/article/172335/supreme-court-lawless">断言</a>。<br><br>哈佛法学院名誉教授马克·图什内特甚至向拜登发出了<a data-event-element="inline link" href="https://balkin.blogspot.com/2023/07/an-open-letter-to-biden-administration.html">一封公开信，</a>敦促他自行决定不服从最高法院的裁决，以“限制 MAGA 的法官”。这一论点并没有比唐纳德·特朗普的律师约翰·伊士曼在 1 月 6 日骚乱之前更加尊重法治和避免宪法危机。<br><br>最高法院并非无可批评。我经常不同意其所有成员和许多多数成员的意见。我相信其法官在道德上有义务举报重大礼物和免费旅行。我更喜欢固定任期，而不是被任命的人一直保住自己的职位直到去世。但对法院 2023 年裁决的评论过于做作，以至于误导了公众对所发生事件的了解。<br><br> <a href="https://www.theatlantic.com/ideas/archive/2022/11/supreme-court-dobbs-conservative-majority/672089/">琳达·格林豪斯：最高法院到底发生了什么？</a><br><br>尽管被指控存在赤裸裸的党派偏见，但最高法院还是做出了多项重大裁决，其中不同党派总统任命的法官同时占多数和少数。共和党任命的法官在多项多数决定中裁定<i>反对</i>共和党立法者的行为。法院的裁决通常符合民意，而不是与民意相悖。 （ <i>《纽约时报》</i>汇总的民意<a data-event-element="inline link" href="https://www.nytimes.com/interactive/2023/06/07/us/major-supreme-court-cases-2023.html">调查</a>显示，只有一项裁决明显偏离了民意，即承认环境保护局对永久性水体的法定管辖权，同时裁定《清洁水法》不赋予其对湿地的管辖权。 ）<br><br>至于意识形态，法院的司法推理和结果都表明，大多数人更多地受到<i>小</i>自由主义价值观的影响，而不是一些反对者声称的“右翼”或“极端主义”价值观。法官们在许多民主党人欢呼的决定中维护了选举的公正性和投票权。在进步派抱怨最多的两项判决中，法院阻止了两个强大机构公然歧视少数种族群体，并遏制了一位总统通过以<a data-event-element="inline link" href="https://www.brookings.edu/articles/student-loan-forgiveness-is-regressive-whether-measured-by-income-education-or-wealth/">转移财富</a>的方式免除债务而故意超越其合法权力。从较贫穷的美国人到较富裕的美国人。<br><br>总的来说，2023 年的多数裁决反映了法官们通过推理得出了在法律上站得住脚、实际上可行的结论，无论你是否同意他们的观点。这些裁决根本没有提供任何依据来质疑法院的合法性，而那些这样做的人不仅目光短浅、轻率，而且具有误导性。<br><br><b>投票权案件</b><br><br>在本学期的两起案件中， <a data-event-element="inline link" href="https://www.supremecourt.gov/search.aspx?filename=/docket/docketfiles/html/public/21-1086.html"><i>即艾伦诉米利根案</i></a>和<a data-event-element="inline link" href="https://www.supremecourt.gov/opinions/22pdf/21-1271_3f14.pdf"><i>摩尔诉哈珀案</i></a>，最高法院审议了共和党控制的州立法机构（一个在阿拉巴马州，另一个在北卡罗来纳州）与诉讼当事人之间的争议，指控他们的行为破坏了公平性。的选举。<br><br>在<a data-event-element="inline link" href="https://supreme.justia.com/cases/federal/us/599/21-1086/#tab-opinion-4749966"><i>艾伦诉米利根一案</i></a>中，最高法院<i>做出了有利于</i>那些认为阿拉巴马州共和党人的选区重新划分计划可能违反《投票权法》的人的裁决。在<i>摩尔诉哈珀一案</i>中，最高法院驳回了右翼的“独立立法机构理论”，该理论认为宪法赋予州立法机构独家的、不可审查的权力来监管联邦选举。在首席大法官约翰·罗伯茨 (John Roberts) 撰写的一份意见中，以 6 比 3 的多数裁定，北卡罗来纳州立法机构对其自己的选区重新划分地图没有排他性、独立的权力：“当州立法机构制定有关联邦选举的规则时，它们仍然受普通选举法的约束。行使国家司法审查权。”<br><br>这两个案件——事实上，它们所涉及的整个法律领域——其复杂性足以令人望而生畏，尽管我很喜欢结果，但我犹豫是否要对它们的法律优点发表意见。它们在这里是相关的，因为如果最高法院实际上是一个右翼机构，共和党任命的人利用他们的多数来推动党派结果，而不考虑法律或长期的先例，那么共和党控制的立法机构在这两种情况下都会获胜。<br><br>相反，民粹右翼共和党计划在这两种情况下都失败了。 （类似地，在<i>《美国诉德克萨斯州》</i>中，以 8 比 1 的多数裁定德克萨斯州和路易斯安那州这两个由共和党控制的州缺乏宪法第三条规定的资格来挑战拜登的移民执法政策。）一些观察家认为<i>摩尔v. 哈珀案</i>对于捍卫美国民主、反对民粹右翼窃取 2020 年选举的努力至关重要。<br><br>律师兼评论员戴维·弗伦奇 (David French) <a data-event-element="inline link" href="https://www.nytimes.com/2023/06/27/opinion/scotus-saved-democracy.html">辩称</a>：“最高法院的裁决剥夺了共和党关于 [2020] 选举因州法院干预而存在法律问题的论点的基础。” “这种干预本质上并不违反联邦宪法，州立法机构也没有非凡的宪法自主权来独立制定选举规则。就2024年及以后而言，最高法院的裁决消除了流氓立法机构制定不受司法审查的新选举规则的能力……换句话说，美国法律的传统制衡机制仍然适用。”<br><br><b>平权行动</b><br><br>如果我告诉你，美国最古老、最强大的公司之一正在对历史上被边缘化的群体进行制度化的种族歧视，你会怎么样？想要加入该机构的年轻人会被其官员分配“个人评级”；在对这些评级进行分析时，少数群体的成员被系统地评为在“正直、乐于助人、勇气、善良、坚韧、同理心、自信、领导能力、成熟或毅力”等<a data-event-element="inline link" href="https://www.harvard.edu/admissionscase/wp-content/uploads/sites/6/2021/06/2019-10-30_dkt_672_findings_of_fact_and_conclusions_of_law.pdf">特质方面</a>相对缺乏。与白人？<br><br>这只是哈佛多年来秘密实施的招生制度丑陋现实的一部分，在该制度中，它对亚裔申请者存在种族歧视。北卡罗来纳大学以不同的方式歧视同一群体。在倒退的种族伪科学的基础上，来自这片庞大而多样化的亚洲大陆的遥远的美国青少年被视为一个团结的群体，并被迫相互竞争席位，这是多么荒谬。<br><br> <a href="https://www.theatlantic.com/podcasts/archive/2023/06/the-end-of-affirmative-action-for-real-this-time/674434/">阅读：平权行动的终结。这次是真的。</a><br><br>在<a data-event-element="inline link" href="https://supreme.justia.com/cases/federal/us/600/20-1199/#tab-opinion-4758916"><i>“学生公平招生公司诉哈佛大学校长和院士”</i></a>和<i>“学生公平招生公司诉北卡罗来纳大学”</i>两起案件中，多数意见否定了大学以名义进行种族歧视的行为的平权行动。对于多数决定的范围是否适当，或者种族主义政策是否应该被更小范围地废除，理性的观察者可能会有所不同。但大多数人都答对了最重要的问题：第十四修正案的平等保护条款和民权法案都不允许基于亚裔血统的公然种族歧视。<br><br>这个问题的道德清晰度不仅在道德上很重要，而且在道德上也很重要。这在政治上也很重要。当进步人士捍卫社会保障等老年权利时，他们认识到此类计划的普遍性与其长期受欢迎是分不开的。我们的民权基础设施也是如此。只要该基础设施保护我们多民族国家的每个人免受种族歧视的侮辱，每个人都将有利于保护它。相比之下，如果民权法保护黑人免受精英的侵害，精英会给他们较低的“个人评价”，但不保护亚洲人——如果它可能会或可能不会保护拉丁裔，并且绝对不会保护白人——许多人会对其崩溃感兴趣。<br><br><b>言论自由和非歧视</b><br><br><a data-event-element="inline link" href="https://www.supremecourt.gov/opinions/22pdf/21-476_c185.pdf"><i>303 Creative LLC 诉 Elenis</i></a>案涉及大多数美国人高度重视的法律的两个不同方面：第一修正案保护国家不得强迫言论，特别是与个人的政治或宗教信仰或良知相悖的言论，以及公民权利防止企业基于种族或性、性别、性取向或其他受保护特征歧视潜在客户的保护措施。当言论自由和非歧视保护陷入紧张时会发生什么？<br><br>有争议的法律，即《科罗拉多州反歧视法》，禁止公共场所基于残疾、种族、信仰、肤色、性别、性取向、婚姻状况、民族血统或血统。<br><br>洛里·史密斯经营着一家销售平面设计、网站设计和营销的小企业。她想开始创建定制婚礼网站，其中包括她庆祝客户婚姻的原创艺术和散文。根据她的宗教传统，即婚姻是一男一女的结合，她不相信同性婚礼实际上会导致婚姻。史密斯担心，如果她开始创建婚礼网站，科罗拉多州民权委员会将迫使她为计划同性婚礼的夫妇提供服务。<br><br>她通常愿意为男同性恋、女同性恋、双性恋和跨性别者客户提供与婚礼无关的项目的客户，并且通常不愿意为任何性取向的任何人做创造性的工作，如果该工作违反了她的信仰——例如，通过鼓励暴力、贬低某人或宣扬无神论。<br><br>和大多数美国人一样，我不太喜欢史密斯关于同性婚姻的信念。但她拒绝进行创造性工作，确认同性婚姻是婚姻，这与<i>基于性取向的</i>歧视在功能上是相同的还是在法律上有区别？根据宪法，如果史密斯开始设计婚礼网站，国家是否可以强迫她创建这样一个网站，以她的原创艺术作品和散文为特色，庆祝同性婚姻？<br><br>根据对第一修正案问题的卡通化的最高主义方法和对公共住宿问题的不谨慎的极简主义方法，法律可以将销售任何商品或服务的行为视为一种表达活动。加油站老板可以拒绝向女同性恋夫妇出售燃料；旅馆老板可以拒绝向他们出租房间；调酒师可以拒绝摇晃他们的鸡尾酒。在非歧视法的卡通式最高主义方法下，国家可以强迫大多数创意专业人士（艺术家、演讲撰稿人、记者）创造他们所憎恶的东西。引用蒂莫西·蒂姆科维奇法官对地方法院裁决的异议，一位不情愿的穆斯林电影导演可能会被迫制作一部带有犹太复国主义信息的电影；可以让无神论者壁画家接受庆祝福音派热情的委托。<br><br>为了避免这种极端情况，区分不同的情况是有帮助的。<br><br>例如：所提供的商品或服务是否真正具有表现力，例如为活动提供喜剧主持人或主题演讲，还是缺乏表现力，例如为活动提供电力或折叠椅？拒绝提供服务是否会给潜在客户带来沉重负担，就像镇上唯一的加油站拒绝向同性恋夫妇出售燃料一样？或者，负担会很小或根本不存在，就像一家跨国工艺品商店不想向一个拥有宜家、好市多和亚马逊 Prime 送货服务的城市的天主教教区出售蜡烛一样？<br><br> <i>303 Creative LLC 诉 Elenis 案</i>的不同寻常之处在于，案件双方在许多此类区别上达成了一致。尼尔·戈萨奇法官的<a data-event-element="inline link" href="https://www.supremecourt.gov/opinions/22pdf/21-476_c185.pdf">多数意见</a>总结了这些无可争议的事项：史密斯将“乐意为任何性取向的客户创建”图形和网站。她不会为任何性取向的客户创作“与圣经真理相矛盾”的内容。她相信婚姻是一男一女的结合，这是“一种真诚的宗教信仰”。史密斯计划的网站“本质上将具有表现力”，并将表达她的信仰，同时庆祝她对以自己名义命名的婚姻的看法，并注明出处。如果史密斯拒绝客户，许多其他公司“提供定制网站设计服务”。<br><br> <a href="https://www.theatlantic.com/ideas/archive/2022/12/lgbtq-first-amendment-supreme-court/672321/">大卫·弗伦奇：本学期最重要的第一修正案案件</a><br><br>因为科罗拉多州规定了所有这些，所以实际上采取了相对最高主义的立场：史密斯如果要制作婚礼网站，就必须为同性婚姻制作网站，即使该作品<i>是</i>表达她的观点和价值观的原创创意表达以她自己的名义；即使她的陈述<i>是</i>真诚的，因此她通常愿意为同性恋客户制作网站，并且通常不愿意以与同性恋者无关的方式制作与她的信仰相悖的网站；即使同性恋伴侣也能轻松找到其他定制网站设计师。<br><br>戈萨奇（他还在 2020 年案件中撰写了多数意见， <a data-event-element="inline link" href="https://www.npr.org/2020/06/15/863498848/supreme-court-delivers-major-victory-to-lgbtq-employees">发现</a>“1964 年民权法案保护同性恋和变性雇员免受歧视”）在他的多数意见中写道，根据科罗拉多州的逻辑，“政府可以强迫任何人如果该主题以某种方式暗示了客户受法定保护的特征，则该主题的付费发言者将接受该主题的所有佣金（无论其背后的信息如何）。严肃地说，这一原则将允许政府强迫各种艺术家、演讲撰稿人和其他涉及言论服务的人说出他们不相信的内容，否则将受到处罚。”<br><br>戈萨奇还小心翼翼地澄清，“我们并不质疑公共设施法在实现所有美国人的公民权利方面发挥的重要作用”，并指出法院不断承认“消除公共设施场所歧视的‘令人信服的利益’， ” and specifying that state governments can protect the access of gay people specifically to “innumerable goods and services that no one could argue implicate the First Amendment.”<br><br> Although the ruling is clear that many public-accommodations laws pass constitutional muster while some “sweep too broadly when deployed to compel speech,” how to decide edge cases is less clear. “Determining what qualifies as expressive activity protected by the First Amendment can sometimes raise difficult questions,” Gorsuch writes. “But this case presents no complication of that kind.” If some future ruling allows a refusal to do business with gay people because of their sexual orientation itself, or starts treating every restaurant owner, innkeeper, plumber, mechanic, and dentist as a creative professional, I&#39;ll worry intensely about the consequences for gay people trying to navigate society equally. But this ruling does not go there.<br><br> As for its practical consequences: Are same-sex couples going to have trouble finding vendors for creative wedding work? Thankfully, no. Seventy-one percent of Americans support gay marriage, as do 89 percent of 18-to-29-year-olds. In her dissent, Justice Sonia Sotomayor frets that a graphic designer refusing to make websites for same-sex weddings will stigmatize gay people; I think wedding-industry folks who refuse to work on same-sex weddings are more likely to create a stigma around their own business. And how many engaged gay couples even want to hire a creative professional who strongly opposes gay marriage to collaborate with them on their wedding?<br><br> Looking back on this case in 20 years, I suspect we&#39;ll conclude that the Court struck a reasonable, practical balancing of rights that continued to afford substantial protections against discrimination in public accommodations––and that its compelled-speech precedent will be invoked again and again by Americans, including gay people and progressives, to vindicate their rights against state actors being coercive in ways that we haven&#39;t even yet anticipated.<br><br> <b>The Student-Debt Cases</b><br><br> In <a data-event-element="inline link" href="https://www.supremecourt.gov/search.aspx?filename=/docket/docketfiles/html/public/22-506.html"><i>Biden v. Nebraska</i></a> and <a data-event-element="inline link" href="https://www.supremecourt.gov/search.aspx?filename=/docket/docketfiles/html/public/22-535.html"><i>Department of Education v. Brown</i></a> , the Court considered the Biden administration&#39;s attempt to cancel student-loan debt. Was the president lawfully empowered to do such a thing, or was he usurping power that properly belongs to Congress? In a 6–3 decision, the Court ruled that the Biden administration&#39;s secretary of education “asserts that the HEROES Act grants him the authority to cancel $430 billion of student loan principal. It does not.”<br><br> Reacting to the decision, Democratic Senator <a data-event-element="inline link" href="https://twitter.com/SenSchumer/status/1674794719048781825">Chuck Schumer</a> declared, “This disappointing and cruel student debt ruling shows the callousness of the MAGA Republican-controlled Supreme Court.” Democratic Senator Elizabeth Warren complained that the Court “refuses to follow the plain language of the law on student loan cancellation,” as if student-loan-debt cancellation was not just lawful but obviously so, such that any contrary finding was bad-faith obstinacy. Love or hate the ruling, those critiques are egregiously misleading.<br><br> That Biden exceeded the lawful authority of the executive branch is not a view original or exclusive to MAGA Republicans. In 2021, the Office of the General Counsel at the Department of Education was asked to weigh in on whether the secretary of education had statutory authority to cancel, discharge, or forgive student loans. “We believe the Secretary does not have the statutory authority,” the resulting memorandum stated in <a data-event-element="inline link" href="https://static.politico.com/d6/ce/3edf6a3946afa98eb13c210afd7d/ogcmemohealoans.pdf">a detailed legal analysis</a> .<br><br> On July 28, 2021, Representative Nancy Pelosi was asked about different approaches to canceling student-loan debt. “People think that the president of the United States has the power for debt forgiveness,” <a data-event-element="inline link" href="https://archive.ph/xCDHb">she said</a> . “He does not. He can postpone. He can delay. But he does not have that power. That has to be an act of Congress … The president can only postpone, delay, but not forgive.”<br><br> Charlie Rose, the top lawyer in President Barack Obama&#39;s Education Department from 2009 to 2011, wrote a legal memo dated May 7, 2021, analyzing the Biden administration&#39;s plan for his law firm, <a data-event-element="inline link" href="https://www.wsj.com/articles/mass-student-debt-cancellation-legally-risky-says-top-obama-education-lawyer-11651689489">according to <i>The Wall Street Journal</i></a> . “If the issue is litigated,” the memo stated, “the more persuasive analyses tend to support the conclusion that the Executive Branch likely does not have the unilateral authority to engage in mass student debt cancellation.”<br><br> Elizabeth Goitein is an expert on presidential powers who was counsel to progressive then-Senator Russ Feingold and a senior director at the Brennan Center for Justice. She addressed the student-loan controversy in a 2022 <i>Washington Post</i> <a data-event-element="inline link" href="https://www.washingtonpost.com/opinions/2022/09/01/biden-student-debt-emergency-powers-are-slippery-slope/">op-ed</a> . “Biden cannot use emergency powers to forgive certain private student loan debts or debts incurred after the covid-19 emergency declaration lapses,” she wrote. “Sidelining Congress through emergency powers means sidelining the checks and balances that safeguard our liberties and democracy.”<br><br> One needn&#39;t even agree with the general counsel at the Department of Education, or the point of view that Pelosi expressed in 2021, or Rose, or Goitein, to see the egregious dishonesty of characterizations like those made by Warren: It is simply false that any reasonable person who reads the plain text of the law sides with Biden. And Congress is free to cancel student-loan debt anytime. The only obstacle to its doing so is the inability of those who favor cancellation to pass such a law, because of insufficient support for it among America&#39;s elected representatives. That is not on the Supreme Court.<br><br> <b>Unanimous and Near-Unanimous Decisions</b><br><br> The most interesting and comprehensible of the unanimous decisions is <a data-event-element="inline link" href="https://supreme.justia.com/cases/federal/us/600/22-174/#tab-opinion-4758923"><i>Groff v. DeJoy</i></a> . This case concerns Gerald Groff, an evangelical Christian who took a job with the United States Postal Service back when that didn&#39;t involve having to work on the Christian sabbath. But times changed: USPS made a deal with Amazon to make deliveries on Sundays.<br><br> To continue observing the sabbath as directed in the Ten Commandments, Groff transferred to escape Amazon&#39;s delivery footprint, ultimately winding up in tiny Holtwood, Pennsylvania, but Amazon, resting for neither man nor God, expanded there too. Groff then started getting written up for refusing to labor on Sundays. So he sued under Title VII of the Civil Rights Act of 1964. In his telling, USPS could accommodate his religious belief “without undue hardship.” For a unanimous Court, Justice Samuel Alito wrote that “undue hardship” is shown “when a burden is substantial in the overall context of an employer&#39;s business,” not when there is any trifling cost (a standard that some lower courts were erroneously adopting due to language in a bygone case). Employers “must show that the burden of granting an accommodation would result in substantial increased costs in relation to the conduct of its particular business,” the Court ruled.<br><br> For better or worse, it sided with a worker against the interests of a large employer. It is likely to marginally benefit religious workers of all faiths while marginally burdening corporations and other businesses. How does this square with characterizations of the Court as “right-wing”?<br><br> Less important for our purposes than the details of <a data-event-element="inline link" href="https://www.supremecourt.gov/search.aspx?filename=/docket/docketfiles/html/public/22-148.html"><i>Jack Daniel&#39;s Properties v. VIP Products LLC</i></a> , a case about a dog toy shaped like a Jack Daniel&#39;s bottle, or the combined <a data-event-element="inline link" href="https://www.supremecourt.gov/search.aspx?filename=/docket/docketfiles/html/public/21-1333.html"><i>Gonzalez v. Google LLC</i></a> and <a data-event-element="inline link" href="https://www.supremecourt.gov/search.aspx?filename=/docket/docketfiles/html/public/21-1496.html"><i>Twitter, Inc. v. Taamneh</i></a> , which concern the responsibilities of social-media companies subject to laws that regulate content, is the fact that all nine justices were able to reach consensus.<br><br> The Court also handed down a 7–2 decision about what constitutes a true threat under the First Amendment; Justices Amy Coney Barrett and Clarence Thomas dissented. Another 7–2 case, <i>Andy Warhol Foundation for the Visual Arts Inc. v. Goldsmith</i> , concerns the professional photographer Lynn Goldsmith, who took a photo in 1981 of the up-and-coming musician Prince. She later granted <i>Vanity Fair</i> a one-time-only license to use the Prince photo as an “artist reference for an illustration”––which turned out to mean that <i>Vanity Fair</i> hired the famous pop artist Andy Warhol to do an illustration of Prince. Warhol created a bunch of different images based on the photo. Among his creations was a silk-screen portrait, <i>Orange Prince</i> , that <i>Vanity Fair</i> ’s parent company reused for a 2016 cover. Was that an infringement of the photographer&#39;s copyright or fair use?<br><br> Siding with the photographer, Sotomayor wrote the majority opinion, joined by Thomas, Alito, Gorsuch, and Barrett, as well as Ketanji Brown Jackson and Brett Kavanagh. Dissenting together were Roberts and Elena Kagan. I have no idea who got that one right, but the shifting coalitions of justices undermine the reductionist narrative of partisans siding with their team.<br><br><b>赌注</b><br><br>Inaccurate characterizations of major institutions are always worth correcting, but the stakes are especially high when the Supreme Court is attacked inaccurately by those seeking to undermine it.<br><br> Insofar as the Court loses its standing and legitimacy, it loses its ability to check and balance future abuses of power by other branches of government and <i>all</i> of its precedents lose their standing.<br><br> The right finds it easier to see the value of a legitimate Supreme Court now that it is sometimes winning. Progressives smarting from last term&#39;s abortion decision might think, on first instinct, that it would be good if the Court lost its influence. But that is shortsighted. Because of <i>Dobbs</i> , the question of abortion has been returned to the political branches of government. If the high court lost its power in American life, proponents of abortion rights would be no better off––the matter would still turn on elected officials at the federal and state levels.<br><br> Whereas if the Court lost its legitimacy––if the people and the political branches ceased to respect its rulings––Americans would lose rights and protections as varied as the constraints on law enforcement in <i>Miranda</i> , the press protections in <i>New York Times Co. v. Sullivan</i> , and the marriage-rights protections in <i>Obergefell</i> . Absent a strong Supreme Court, I tremble to think how the most retrograde Deep South legislators would draw redistricting maps and constrain voting rights.<br><br> So what would I suggest for Democrats and progressives who dislike the current Court majority and wish to reverse its rulings? Harken back to the days of the Warren Court, regarded by many as an especially left-leaning era, and the days of the Rehnquist Court and beyond, when conservatives thought they&#39;d succeeded in electing presidents who appointed a majority they liked, only to see abortion and affirmative action upheld. In those days, when conservatives were losing ground, or failing to win it back despite decades of effort, what would you have seen as legitimate criticism and what would you have regarded as corrosive attacks on the legitimacy of the judiciary? Let that––and truth––be your guides. Meanwhile, practice tolerance, forbearance, and persuasion, and win elections. Another era of the Court always comes.<br><br></div> ]]>;</description><pubDate> Tue, 01 Aug 2023 11:00:00 GMT</pubDate><guid ispermalink="false"> https://www.theatlantic.com/ideas/archive/2023/08/defense-supreme-court/674874/</guid><link/> https://www.theatlantic.com/ideas/archive/2023/08/defense-supreme-court/674874/ </item><item><title><![CDATA[Trump’s Inevitability Problem]]></title><description><![CDATA[<div> His apparent stranglehold on the GOP race is both emboldening and hindering. <br><figure><img src="https://cdn.theatlantic.com/thumbor/pItqRQjM6NijNJzJjGhB2qfety4=/0x312:6000x3687/960x540/media/img/mt/2023/07/GettyImages_1577576024-1/original.jpg" alt="7 月 28 日，唐纳德·特朗普 (Donald Trump) 在 2023 年林肯晚宴上向宾客致意。" referrerpolicy="no-referrer"><figcaption> Scott Olson / Getty</figcaption></figure><small><i>这是</i>《大西洋<i>日报》的一个版本，是一份时事通讯，可引导您了解当天最大的故事，帮助您发现新想法，并推荐最好的文化。</i> <a data-event-element="inline link" href="https://www.theatlantic.com/newsletters/sign-up/atlantic-daily/"><i>在这里注册。</i></a></small><br><br> There&#39;s Donald Trump, and there&#39;s everyone else. At the moment, the former president of the United States appears unbeatable in the 2024 Republican primary race. But perhaps <i>inevitable</i> is a trickier word than it seems.<br><br> First, here are three new stories from <i>The Atlantic</i> :<br><br><li> <a href="https://www.theatlantic.com/international/archive/2023/07/ukraine-kakhovka-dam-destruction-gallery/674806/">Ukraine after the deluge</a></li><li> <a href="https://www.theatlantic.com/ideas/archive/2023/07/christian-church-communitiy-participation-drop/674843/">The misunderstood reason millions of Americans stopped going to church</a></li><li> <a href="https://www.theatlantic.com/science/archive/2023/07/summer-covid-wave-2023/674863/">One more COVID summer?</a></li> <strong>It&#39;s Iowa Time</strong><br><br> What happens when you say the unsayable? Former Representative (and current GOP presidential contender) <a data-event-element="inline link" href="https://www.theatlantic.com/ideas/archive/2022/03/will-hurd-2024-book/629398/">Will Hurd</a> found out the hard way Friday night. “Donald Trump is not running for president to make America great again,” Hurd told the Republican masses inside the Iowa Events Center. “Donald Trump is running to stay out of prison.”<br><br> The boos rained down, and, rest assured, they were mighty.<br><br> Hurd was one of 13 candidates who had trekked to Des Moines for the Iowa GOP&#39;s <a data-event-element="inline link" href="https://www.desmoinesregister.com/story/news/elections/presidential/caucus/2023/07/28/iowa-gop-lincoln-dinner-draws-2024-contenders-to-des-moines-friday/70457582007/">cattle-call event</a> known as the Lincoln Dinner. Prospective voters and donors gathered roughly six months ahead of Iowa&#39;s first-in-the-nation caucus to remind themselves of their importance, which may or may not be <a data-event-element="inline link" href="https://www.theatlantic.com/politics/archive/2022/12/iowa-caucus-democrats-dnc-vote-2024-presidential-primary-election/672444/">waning</a> . The night was ostensibly a chance for Iowans to listen to a range of electability pitches. Former Vice President Mike Pence told the room he would reinstate a ban on transgender personnel in the US military and endorsed the idea of a national abortion restriction after 15 weeks. The businessman Vivek Ramaswamy rattled off a list of government agencies he would shut down: the FBI, CDC, DOE, ATF, and IRS. Florida Governor Ron DeSantis boasted that he had refused to let his state “descend into a Faucian dystopia” during the pandemic and called for term limits in Congress. (One dinner attendee, the 89-year-old Iowa Senator Chuck Grassley—currently serving his eighth term—probably didn&#39;t like that one.)<br><br> The whole spectacle—including the after-parties where you could snap selfies with candidates or, at the DeSantis event, knock down a pyramid of Bud Light cans—felt like a study in performative competition.<br><br> Each speaker was given a democratizing 10-minute time limit to deliver his or her remarks (poor Asa Hutchinson suffered the embarrassment of having his mic cut off), but all were merely warm-up acts for the headliner. When Trump finally took the stage, he seemed tired, bored, and annoyed with this obligation. A lack of teleprompters meant that Trump spent the bulk of his 10 minutes looking down at printed notes, only occasionally making eye contact with the audience or ad-libbing. He got a few chuckles out of his old pandemic go-to, the “China virus.” He notably referred to his White House predecessor as “Barack Hussein Obama.” The only newish development was that Ron “DeSanctimonious” had been shortened to the easier-to-say but far more confusing “DeSanctis.”<br><br> Trump is not running as an incumbent, but it sure seems that way. A <a data-event-element="inline link" href="https://www.nytimes.com/2023/07/31/us/politics/2024-poll-nyt-siena-trump-republicans.html"><i>New York Times</i> /Siena College poll out today</a> shows Trump with a 37-point lead over DeSantis, who was the only other candidate able to crack double digits among respondents. Did January 6 matter? Do the indictments matter? Does <i>anything</i> remotely negative about Trump matter?还没有。 Trump remains the Katie Ledecky of the 2024 contest—so far ahead of the pack that it feels wrong to even call it a race. Trump knows it too. He may not even bother to show up at the first Republican debate next month, in Milwaukee.<br><br> These factors would suggest that the Republican Party is delaying the inevitable, that the GOP base earnestly wants to “Make America great again” … again. And yet, the various campaign buses keep on rolling across Iowa and New Hampshire. The noble attempts at retail politics and down-home charm continue apace. Pence strategically name-dropped the Iowa chain Pizza Ranch. Senator Tim Scott of South Carolina tweeted a video of himself fist-pumping after <a data-event-element="inline link" href="https://twitter.com/votetimscott/status/1685070929343229952">sinking a bag in cornhole</a> . (“If God made you a man, you play sports against men,” Scott said onstage Friday night.) Expect <a data-event-element="inline link" href="https://www.theatlantic.com/newsletters/archive/2023/06/the-secret-presidential-campaign-dress-code/674298/">much more of this</a> at the Iowa State Fair, which kicks off in just over a week.<br><br> I was in the press pen at the Lincoln Dinner on Friday night, and I spent the weekend in Iowa speaking with various Republicans about all things 2024. I came away with the sense that a not-insignificant portion of conservatives is willing to accept Trump&#39;s dominance, but that many are still quietly hoping for a deus ex machina to avoid a 2020 rematch. The still-rolling indictments don&#39;t seem to have much effect—too many Republican voters argue that the legal cases against Trump are politically motivated. He shows no signs of giving up his nickname, “Teflon Don.”<br><br> The fact that Trump is running from a stance of inevitability is paradoxically both emboldening and hindering. Trump doesn&#39;t seem to want to actually be president (as Hurd suggested). Maybe he just wants to prove he can win again. Will that motivational gap matter to voters? Will <i>anything</i> matter?<br><br> <b>Related</b> :<br><br><li> <a href="https://www.theatlantic.com/ideas/archive/2022/03/will-hurd-2024-book/629398/">The revenge of the normal Republicans</a></li><li> <a href="https://www.theatlantic.com/newsletters/archive/2023/06/the-secret-presidential-campaign-dress-code/674298/">The secret presidential-campaign dress code</a></li> <strong>Today&#39;s News</strong><br><br><li> A state judge in Georgia <a href="https://www.nytimes.com/2023/07/31/us/trump-georgia-prosecutor-election.html">rejected</a> Trump&#39;s bid to derail the investigation into his attempts to overturn election results in the state.</li><li> A <a href="https://www.reuters.com/world/europe/russian-missile-strike-hits-kryvyi-rih-ukraine-interior-ministry-2023-07-31/">Russian missile strike</a> on Kryvyi Rih, President Volodymyr Zelensky&#39;s hometown, killed at least six people, including a 10-year-old girl and her mother, and wounded dozens more.</li><li> The Islamic State <a href="https://www.reuters.com/world/asia-pacific/pakistan-suicide-bombing-death-toll-rises-45-2023-07-31/">claimed responsibility</a> for Sunday&#39;s suicide bombing of a political rally in Pakistan that killed at least 54 people.</li> <strong>Dispatches</strong><br><br><li> <a href="https://www.theatlantic.com/newsletters/sign-up/the-wonder-reader/"><b>The Wonder Reader</b></a> <b>:</b> In 1980, the film critic Roger Ebert argued that movies were better in theaters. The recent success of <i>Barbenheimer</i> is evidence—and points to the ongoing magic of communal experiences, <a href="https://www.theatlantic.com/newsletters/archive/2023/07/movie-going-experience-roger-ebert/674868/">Isabel Fattal writes</a> .</li> <em><a data-event-element="inline link" href="https://link.theatlantic.com/click/29767897.0/aHR0cHM6Ly93d3cudGhlYXRsYW50aWMuY29tL25ld3NsZXR0ZXJzLz91dG1fc291cmNlPW5ld3NsZXR0ZXImdXRtX21lZGl1bT1lbWFpbCZ1dG1fY2FtcGFpZ249YXRsYW50aWMtZGFpbHktbmV3c2xldHRlciZ1dG1fY29udGVudD0yMDIyMTEyMQ/61813432e16c7128e42f4628B52865c35">Explore all of our newsletters here.</a></em><br><br> <b>Evening Read</b><br><br> The Myopia Generation<br><br> <em>By Sarah Zhang</em><br><br><p> A decade into her optometry career, Marina Su began noticing something unusual about the kids in her New York City practice. More of them were requiring glasses, and at younger and younger ages. Many of these kids had parents who had perfect vision and who were baffled by the decline in their children&#39;s eyesight. Frankly, Su couldn&#39;t explain it either.</p><p> In optometry school, she had been taught—as American textbooks had been teaching for decades—that nearsightedness, or myopia, is a genetic condition. Having one parent with myopia doubles the odds that a kid will need glasses. Having two parents with myopia quintuples them. Over the years, she did indeed diagnose lots of nearsighted kids with nearsighted parents. These parents, she told me, would sigh in recognition: <i>Oh no, not them too.</i> But something was changing.</p> <a data-event-element="inline link" href="https://www.theatlantic.com/magazine/archive/2022/10/kids-glasses-vision-increased-nearsightedness-myopia/671244/">阅读全文。</a><br><br> <b>More From <em>The Atlantic</em></b><br><br><li> <a href="https://www.theatlantic.com/health/archive/2023/07/fitboxing-classes-sparring-noncontact/674869/">What “fitboxing” is missing</a></li><li> <a href="https://www.theatlantic.com/international/archive/2023/07/speaking-ukrainian-russian-language/674860/">“Ukrainian is my native language, but I had to learn it.”</a></li><li> <a href="https://www.theatlantic.com/ideas/archive/2023/07/twitter-alternatives-bluesky-mastodon-threads/674859/">The weird, fragmented world of social media after Twitter</a></li><li> <a href="https://www.theatlantic.com/technology/archive/2023/07/ups-strike-union-contract-package-deliveries/674864/">America is drowning in packages.</a></li> <b>Culture Break</b><br><br><b>读。</b> “ <a data-event-element="inline link" href="https://www.theatlantic.com/books/archive/2023/07/poem-michael-white-i-wish-i-could-remember/674867/">I Wish I Could Remember</a> ,” a new poem by Michael White.<br><br> “ <i>It&#39;s just a dream</i> , / I&#39;d tell myself. But dreams are how / we travel through the dark”<br><br> <b>Watch.</b> Biopics tend to be “functional to a fault,” better at showcasing an actor than creating challenging art—but these 20 movies manage to <a data-event-element="inline link" href="https://www.theatlantic.com/culture/archive/2023/02/biopic-movies-first-man-tick-tick-boom/673226/">break the mold</a> , David Sims writes.<br><br><a data-event-element="inline link" href="https://www.theatlantic.com/free-daily-crossword-puzzle/">Play our daily crossword.</a><br><br><strong>聚苯乙烯</strong><br><br>Last week, the podcast host Jack Wagner went viral on Twitter (er, X) with <a data-event-element="inline link" href="https://twitter.com/jackdwagner/status/1683528649855897600">a prompt</a> : “serious question: if the grateful dead is not the greatest band of all time from the united states then who is?” Thousands of responses poured in: The Beach Boys, The Allman Brothers Band, and The Velvet Underground kept surfacing among the many retorts (as did Bruce Springsteen and Tom Petty; I don&#39;t think you can really count either, because even though they play with backing bands, they&#39;re solo artists.) I&#39;m a Deadhead, but the strongest contender I saw was Creedence Clearwater Revival. CCR&#39;s <i>Willy and the Poor Boys</i> remains one of the greatest rock records ever. You likely know “Fortunate Son” and “Down on the Corner,” but the album also features an awesome cover of <a data-event-element="inline link" href="https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=kNiUfwHJF6E">“The Midnight Special”</a> —I love the moment when the whole band kicks in just after the one-minute mark.<br><br> — John<br><br> <i>Nicole Blackwood contributed to this newsletter.</i><br><br> <em>When you buy a book using a link in this newsletter, we receive a commission. Thank you for supporting</em> The Atlantic <em>.</em><br><br></div> ]]>;</description><pubDate> Mon, 31 Jul 2023 22:31:00 GMT</pubDate><guid ispermalink="false"> https://www.theatlantic.com/newsletters/archive/2023/07/trump-2024-election-lead-lincoln-dinner/674877/</guid><link/> https://www.theatlantic.com/newsletters/archive/2023/07/trump-2024-election-lead-lincoln-dinner/674877/ </item><item><title><![CDATA[The Ugly Honesty of Elon Musk’s Twitter Rebrand]]></title><description><![CDATA[<div> The platform&#39;s new logo seems a little juvenile. So does the internet. <br><figure><img src="https://cdn.theatlantic.com/thumbor/t7BDtYVKp8MpaERxjMGJdYeYExo=/0x0:2000x1125/960x540/media/img/mt/2023/07/twitter_final/original.jpg" alt="蓝色鸟舍的照片插图，上面画有黑色“X”" referrerpolicy="no-referrer"><figcaption> Photo-illustration by Ben Kothe / The Atlantic.资料来源：盖蒂。</figcaption></figure> I woke up Sunday to find I had begun using the social network formerly known as Twitter. The app had updated to show the new name chosen by its owner: X. Now, underneath the friendly and familiar blue icon with a white bird, that letter alone was displayed— <em>X</em> —as if my iPhone was affirming that Elon Musk&#39;s Twitter had become an error. Soon after, the bird icon disappeared, too, in favor of a <a data-event-element="inline link" href="https://www.fastcompany.com/90927535/elon-musk-twitter-logo">white-on-black 𝕏</a> .<br><br> The change has rolled out slowly. First the website rebranded, and then, by the end of last week, Musk had dismantled the Twitter signage on the company&#39;s San Francisco headquarters and <a data-event-element="inline link" href="https://apnews.com/article/twitter-san-francisco-building-x-elon-musk-4e0ae2a3b1b838b744bb2dc494f5b23c">erected a huge, glowing <em>X</em></a> on its rooftop. (It has since been <a data-event-element="inline link" href="https://abc7news.com/twitter-x-sign-taken-down-bright-light-sf/13578182/">taken down</a> .) Reprising the creeper thinking that inspired Musk to name Tesla&#39;s models the “S,” “3,” “X,” and “Y,” such that they would combine to spell “ <a data-event-element="inline link" href="https://electrek.co/2016/07/30/tesla-vehicle-naming-convention-sexy-model-y-elon-musk/">S3XY</a> ,” Twitter also reportedly gave several conference rooms new, <em>X</em> -oriented names, including “eXposure” and, once again, “ <a data-event-element="inline link" href="https://www.nytimes.com/2023/07/24/technology/twitter-x-elon-musk.html">s3Xy</a> .”<br><br> As my colleague Charlie Warzel <a data-event-element="inline link" href="https://www.theatlantic.com/technology/archive/2023/07/twitter-musk-x-rebrand/674818/">explained last week</a> , Musk has been trying to make X happen for decades now; PayPal arose from a merger with his X.com website. Now he&#39;d like for X to be a superapp, a platform for chat, banking, news, shopping—everything. Musk&#39;s insistence on packaging that idea, already megalomaniacal, with a logo that resembles a nerdy middle-school boy&#39;s notebook doodle underscores a difficult truth: Nerdy middle-school boyhood, once a phase to be outgrown, has become a philosophy of life. “Anyone else look at the 𝕏 icon and not even want to open this app?” the Chicago-based product designer Chad Ashley tweeted—err, <a data-event-element="inline link" href="https://twitter.com/cgpov/status/1685616291703410688">posted on X</a> .他是对的。太丢脸了。<br><br> Maybe that&#39;s for the best. As a cultural practice, social media is bad— <a data-event-element="inline link" href="https://www.theatlantic.com/technology/archive/2021/10/fix-facebook-making-it-more-like-google/620456/">people aren&#39;t meant to talk to one another this much</a> —and anything that might erode the practice is worthwhile. But also, Twitter, like other social platforms and the very internet itself, is already redolent of the seventh grader&#39;s mindset that Musk&#39;s behavior betrays. Maybe we should be grateful that his X fetish forces us to admit that truth, so we can someday move beyond it.<br><br> In its un-rebranded form, Twitter helped make the lifestyle of posting seem benign. Before it was a company (and then an online addiction), <em>twitter</em> was just a word: a reference to the sound of birds or certain kinds of human prattle. What harm could come of that?<br><br> Lots. For starters, it normalized the very notion of a platform where everyone can speak to everyone, all at once. This feels natural today, but it wasn&#39;t when the service launched in 2006. Back then, some might have had a blog, but people ordinarily posted only to small, closed online networks. That&#39;s how Facebook still worked, and LinkedIn too, and Orkut, may it rest in peace. Social networks were initially designed around communities of trust. Twitter and then Instagram are to blame for expanding the act of posting to the world.<br><br> The shift from social networks to social media was <a data-event-element="inline link" href="https://www.theatlantic.com/technology/archive/2022/11/twitter-facebook-social-media-decline/672074/">culturally destructive</a> . It set the expectation that everyone deserves—is owed, even—an audience for their every notion, quip, photo, or activity. This is a selfish child&#39;s idea of living in the world, now so commonplace that opposing it seems controversial.<br><br> That ethos has consequences. The rise of public shaming online, whether <a data-event-element="inline link" href="http://www.nytimes.com/2015/02/15/magazine/how-one-stupid-tweet-ruined-justine-saccos-life.html?_r=0">in response to jokes</a> , to <a data-event-element="inline link" href="https://www.theatlantic.com/science/archive/2016/02/the-evolution-of-shaming/470544/">affirm personal virtue</a> , or to <a data-event-element="inline link" href="https://www.theatlantic.com/ideas/archive/2020/05/best-shaming-happens-private/612082/">deepen group membership</a> , was dependent on an infrastructure of public data from which shameworthiness could be assessed, and also on the viral spread that Twitter both invented and perfected. So was the spread of QAnon, and the planning for the January 6 insurgency. The ability to repost something instantly and without comment to one&#39;s own network, first invented as the “retweet button” in 2009, became a <a data-event-element="inline link" href="https://www.buzzfeednews.com/article/alexkantrowitz/how-the-retweet-ruined-the-internet">vector for harassment and misinformation</a> , allowing messages true or false, virtuous or vicious, to reach far beyond their original environments. Every other platform adopted a version of this feature because of its ability to produce engagement, and now imagining social media without it is almost impossible.<br><br> <a href="https://www.theatlantic.com/technology/archive/2022/11/twitter-facebook-social-media-decline/672074/">Read: The age of social media is ending</a><br><br> Those are influences of function—many frequently acknowledged. Less discussed: Twitter and the services it influenced also changed aesthetic life. They brought a new style to the fore: juvenile narcissism. X is its purest, dumbest distillation, a seemingly edgy but ultimately corny name that evokes mathematics and nightclubs, pornography and tabletop games.<br><br> Like many styles, Musk&#39;s (and Twitter&#39;s) came out of a subculture, and one that thrives online. The infinity of social media creates communities at the fringe. In the best cases, these improve the lives of people who might otherwise struggle for connection, but they can also serve as bubbles that amplify and normalize perversion. When everyone can find a group of like-minded individuals, all flavors of mindedness can end up seeming justified—including, most of all, the weird-schoolboy-mindedness of the people who happen to have invented the internet as we know it.<br><br> Online culture began in corners where weirdos could connect. Dialed into local <a data-event-element="inline link" href="https://www.theatlantic.com/technology/archive/2016/11/the-lost-civilization-of-dial-up-bulletin-board-systems/506465/">BBSes</a> , or logged on to Usenet threads and text-based virtual worlds called MUDs, nerds and outcasts were the first to find their tribes online. Some shared recipes or crochet patterns; others expressed their board-game, anime, or furry fandoms; while still others passed around conspiracy theories. And there were always piles and piles of naked pictures.<br><br> Across many of these communities, no matter their host, content, or members, an ethos of dorky behavior was ascendant—and it persists today. You can&#39;t browse a subreddit for plumbing or coffee-brewing tips without running the risk of wading through a hundred nested replies containing dumb jokes, sneers, and sexual innuendo. Bizarre beliefs that once would have been confined to email forwards became widespread on Facebook. Every tweet becomes an opportunity for some miscreant, mansplainer, or literalist to pick your words apart. The <a data-event-element="inline link" href="https://simpsons.fandom.com/wiki/Comic_Book_Guy">Comic Book Guys</a> took over.<br><br> Sexual desire and frustration, familiar feelings for the outcast teenage nerd, pervade the social internet. S3xy-ness is everywhere. Posts by women are dismayingly likely to produce advances, or threats, from creepers on all platforms; at the same time, sex appeal is a pillar for the influencer economy, or else a <a data-event-element="inline link" href="https://www.nytimes.com/2019/02/09/style/onlyfans-porn-stars.html">viable</a> and even noble way to win financial independence. <a data-event-element="inline link" href="https://knowyourmeme.com/memes/the-internet-is-for-porn">The internet is for porn</a> , as the song goes.<br><br> In all these ways, online life today descends from where it started, as a safe harbor for the computer nerds who made it. They were socially awkward, concerned with machines instead of people, and devoted to the fantasy of converting their impotence into power. When that conversion was achieved, and the nerds took over the world, they adopted the bravado of the jocks they once despised. ( <a data-event-element="inline link" href="https://www.theatlantic.com/technology/archive/2023/06/musk-zuckerberg-cage-fight-social-media-supremacy/674503/">Zuck-Musk cage match</a> , anyone?) But they didn&#39;t stop being nerds. We, the public, never agreed to adopt their worldview as the basis for political, social, or aesthetic life. We got it nevertheless.<br><br> <a href="https://www.theatlantic.com/technology/archive/2023/06/musk-zuckerberg-cage-fight-social-media-supremacy/674503/">Read: The nerds are bullies now</a><br><br> Musk&#39;s obsession with X as a brand, and his childish desire to broadcast that obsession from the rooftops in hoggish, <a data-event-element="inline link" href="https://abc7news.com/twitter-x-sign-bright-light-sf-hq/13575800/">bright pulsations</a> , calls attention to this baggage. It reminds us that the world&#39;s richest man is a computer geek, but one with enormous power instead of none. It calls attention to the putrid smell that suffuses the history of the internet. I&#39;m kind of tired of pretending that the stench does not exist, as if doing otherwise would be tantamount to expressing prejudice against neurodivergence. This is a bad culture, and it always has been.<br><br> Foul nerddom is part of what invented, popularized, and profited from the internet&#39;s commercial rise. Twitter did its part to hide all that, with its unoffending avian verbs, its adorable birds, even its charming <a data-event-element="inline link" href="https://www.theatlantic.com/technology/archive/2015/01/the-story-behind-twitters-fail-whale/384313/">fail whale</a> . Better we should understand that no global attention network is ever really cute or charming, for they all are on the internet, a cesspool.<br><br> If the X rebrand disgusts you—if, like me, you&#39;ve been made a little queasy by having the new logo thrust upon your phone via automatic update—that feeling is about more than Musk alone. He has merely surfaced what has been there all along. The internet is magical and empowering. The internet is childish and disgusting.<br><br></div> ]]>;</description><pubDate> Mon, 31 Jul 2023 21:15:26 GMT</pubDate><guid ispermalink="false"> https://www.theatlantic.com/technology/archive/2023/07/twitter-x-rebrand-juvenile-internet-style/674875/</guid><link/> https://www.theatlantic.com/technology/archive/2023/07/twitter-x-rebrand-juvenile-internet-style/674875/ </item><item><title><![CDATA[After the Deluge]]></title><description><![CDATA[<div>卡霍夫卡大坝因涉嫌俄罗斯破坏而被毁，使乌克兰土地本身成为战争的牺牲品。 <br><figure><img src="https://cdn.theatlantic.com/thumbor/XjGFqHJvx-VOn6AIEPcrbV-ShhE=/0x381:5019x3204/1440x810/media/img/2023/07/24/JN013_The_Atlantic_230629_Kakhovka_Dam_Final_Edit/original.jpg" alt="两个孩子把一根棍子插进干涸水库的泥里。" referrerpolicy="no-referrer"><figcaption>杰德热·诺维茨基</figcaption></figure><small>这篇文章发表在《今日必读的一个故事》中，这是一份时事通讯，我们的编辑在其中推荐了《大西洋月刊<i>》周一至周五</i><i>必读的一篇文章</i>。 <a data-event-element="inline link" data-saferedirecturl="https://www.google.com/url?q=https://www.theatlantic.com/newsletters/sign-up/one-story-to-read-today/&amp;source=gmail&amp;ust=1690911809377000&amp;usg=AOvVaw1sq1uWHi-_hXFssF5-6cC7" href="https://www.theatlantic.com/newsletters/sign-up/one-story-to-read-today/" target="_blank"><i>在这里注册。</i></a> <i>&nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp;</i></small> <br><br><style type="text/css">.left-aligned-caption figcaption {
